Leptospirosis: A bacterial infection causing fever, muscle aches, jaundice, hemorrhage, headache, and gastrointestinal and neurological symptoms. Leptospirosis symptoms may mimic dengue fever; however, dengue fever causes eye pain, while leptospirosis does not. Also, dengue fever causes a rapid pulse, while leptospirosis typically does not.

Cytomegalovirus: A double-stranded DNA virus causing mononucleosis and congenital malformations if the mother contracts it when pregnant. Fatigue, fatigue, lethargy, malaise, splenomegaly, elevated liver enzymes, and pneumonia are signs to watch for. It usually presents with fever that is higher than fever in dengue; however, they both may cause headache.

Dengue Fever: An acute disease from the bite of an infected mosquito that may cause muscle, joint, and eye pain and a fever higher than usual, as well as skin flushing. In severe cases, there may be hemorrhage, organ impairment, and plasma leakage; in these cases, there is a higher mortality rate than dengue hemorrhagic fever without prompt treatment. In mild cases, it may look like other diseases, such as leptospirosis; however, dengue fever causes eye pain, while leptospirosis does not. Also, dengue fever causes a rapid pulse, while leptospirosis typically does not. In severe cases, it may look like dengue hemorrhagic fever; however, dengue hemorrhagic fever progresses rapidly in severe cases. Also, dengue fever, in the beginning, has a different platelet count trend than it does in severe cases.

Herpes Simplex Virus-1 (Oral Herpes): A virus with two strains and three patterns: oral, genital, and neonatal. HSV-1 typically presents as vesicles and/or erosions of the skin or eyes; a prodrome (tingling, burning) may occur with primary infection. In a neonatal infection that was acquired while passing through the vaginal canal, infants will show lethargy, seizures, skin lesions of various ages, or respiratory difficulty. It typically has fewer symptoms than Epstein-Barr Virus, a disease with similar symptoms; however, Epstein-Barr virus causes a sore throat in most cases, whereas it is uncommon in Herpes Simplex.

Influenza: An acute contagious respiratory illness caused by an influenza virus, spread through coughing, sneezing, and close contact. The disease may cause fever, sore throat, muscle aches, fatigue, cough, runny or stuffy nose, headache, chills, vomiting, and diarrhea. Its symptoms, such as cough and runny nose, overlap largely with those of SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19); however, SARS-CoV-2 typically causes shortness of breath.

Lyme Disease: A disease from the bite of infected ticks causing a bulls eye rash, fever, chills, headache, fatigue, and muscle and joint aches in the first stage; untreated, the second stage involves neurological issues and cardiac abnormalities, while the late stage has disabling arthritis. Fatigue is a prominent feature, often being the earliest and most persistent symptom; sometimes, fatigue and joint, muscle, head, or neck pain are the only symptoms experienced. In untreated cases, it may look like rheumatoid arthritis; however, tests can distinguish these two diseases.

Mononucleosis: An infectious mononucleosis disease with fatigue, low-grade fever, pharyngitis, and lymphadenopathy primarily affecting adolescents and young adults. In most cases, spleen enlargement happens. In complications, splenic rupture is the highest cause for hospitalization; also, there are hematologic problems and airway complications like respiratory obstruction. It typically has a lower fever than Parvovirus B19, a disease with similar symptoms; however, Parvovirus B19 also causes a widespread rash that mononucleosis typically does not. Also, Mononucleosis has the potential for splenic rupture, which Parvovirus B19 does not typically.

Parvovirus B19, Fifth Disease/Erythema Infectiosum: A common disease of childhood with flu-like symptoms, a bright red facial rash (slapped-cheek appearance), and a lacy red rash on the limbs and trunk that may itch. The rash varies in appearance; there may be no rash, there may be only a red face, there may be only a lacy rash, or there may be all three. It typically has a higher fever than mononucleosis, a disease with similar symptoms; however, Parvovirus B19 may also cause a widespread rash which mononucleosis typically does not. Also, Mononucleosis has the potential for splenic rupture, which Parvovirus B19 does not typically.

Rubeola (Measles): A highly contagious virus with severe complications like pneumonia and encephalitis; symptoms are seen 10 to 12 days post infection in three stages including prodrome of cough, coryza, conjunctivitis, Kopliks spots, high fever, malaise, headache, photophobia, rash, and sometimes diarrhea and vomiting. Rubeola (measles) may look like roseola infantum; however, measles presents with severe respiratory symptoms.

Roseola Infantum: A childhood viral infection causing high fever for three days then rash, but not much else. Some children have febrile seizures. Typically, symptoms appear six to fifteen days post infection after a 5- to 7-day incubation period. It can manifest in a variety of ways or look a lot like other diseases; it can even cause no symptoms. Rubeola (measles) may look like roseola infantum; however, measles presents with severe respiratory symptoms.

description: Acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) is a cancer of the blood and bone marrow. It is the most common type of childhood leukemia. ALL can also occur in adults, but it is much less common. In adults, ALL is usually more aggressive than in children. ALL is characterized by the rapid growth of abnormal lymphocytes, a type of white blood cell. These abnormal lymphocytes crowd out normal blood cells, leading to anemia, infection, and bleeding problems. The exact number of people in the United States diagnosed with ALL each year is not available, but around 6,000 adults are diagnosed each year. The exact cause of ALL is unknown, but it is thought to be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. There is no cure for ALL, but treatment can lead to long-term remission. Treatment typically consists of chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and bone marrow transplantation. The prognosis for ALL varies depending on the age of the patient and the type of ALL. In children, the five-year survival rate is around 90%. In adults, the five-year survival rate is around 40%.

description: A type of migraine headache that is preceded by an aura, which is a temporary neurological disturbance that can include visual disturbances, sensory disturbances, or speech disturbances.
prevalence: 18% of people experience migraines, 25% of those experience auras.
risk factors: Genetics, stress, hormonal changes, caffeine withdrawal, sleep disturbances, certain foods and drinks.
symptoms: Scintillations, parasthesias, headache, nausea, vomiting, light sensitivity, sound sensitivity.
treatment: Pain medications, anti-nausea medications, triptans, preventive medications.
description: A temporary interruption of blood flow to the brain, which can cause symptoms similar to those of a stroke. TIAs are often called \mini-strokes\.
prevalence: Approximately 1 in 3 people over the age of 65 will have a TIA.
risk factors: High blood pressure, high cholesterol, diabetes, smoking, obesity, carotid artery disease.
symptoms: Sudden numbness or weakness, especially on one side of the body; difficulty speaking or understanding speech; dizziness; vision problems; headache.
treatment: Urgent medical attention to identify the cause of the TIA and prevent a stroke.
description: A neurological disorder characterized by recurrent seizures, which are sudden bursts of electrical activity in the brain.
prevalence: Approximately 1% of people worldwide have epilepsy.
risk factors: Genetics, head injury, stroke, brain tumor, infection.
symptoms: Seizures, which can vary in severity from brief episodes of staring to loss of consciousness and convulsions.
treatment: Anti-seizure medications, surgery, vagus nerve stimulation.
description: An abnormal growth of cells in the brain.
prevalence: Approximately 1 in 100 people will develop a brain tumor at some point in their lifetime.
risk factors: Genetics, radiation exposure, certain chemicals.
symptoms: Headaches, seizures, vision problems, weakness, numbness, confusion, personality changes.
description: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the central nervous system.
prevalence: Approximately 2.3 million people worldwide have MS.
risk factors: Genetics, environmental factors, Epstein-Barr virus infection.
symptoms: Scintillations, parasthesias, fatigue, weakness, numbness, vision problems, bladder and bowel problems.
treatment: Disease-modifying therapies, steroids, physical therapy, occupational therapy.
description: A chronic pain disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain, fatigue, and sleep disturbances.
prevalence: Approximately 2% of adults in the United States have fibromyalgia.
risk factors: Genetics, physical or emotional trauma, infections.
symptoms: Widespread pain, fatigue, stiffness, sleep disturbances, cognitive difficulties, headaches, irritable bowel syndrome.
treatment: Pain medications, antidepressants, anticonvulsants, physical therapy, lifestyle changes.
description: A condition that affects the bones and discs in the neck, often due to wear and tear over time.
prevalence: Approximately 85% of people over the age of 60 have cervical spondylosis.
risk factors: Age, genetics, repetitive strain, poor posture.
symptoms: Neck pain, stiffness, headaches, numbness or weakness in the arms or hands, dizziness.
treatment: Pain medications, physical therapy, surgery.
description: A type of vasculitis, or inflammation of the blood vessels, that affects the arteries in the head, including the temporal arteries.
prevalence: Approximately 1 in 10,000 people over the age of 50 have giant cell arteritis.
risk factors: Age, female gender, northern European ancestry.
symptoms: Headaches, scalp tenderness, jaw pain, vision problems, fever, fatigue.
description: A pregnancy complication characterized by high blood pressure and signs of damage to other organ systems, such as the liver or kidneys.
prevalence: Approximately 5-8% of pregnancies worldwide are affected by pre-eclampsia.
risk factors: First-time pregnancy, multiple gestation, pre-existing medical conditions such as high blood pressure or diabetes.
symptoms: Sudden onset of high blood pressure, protein in the urine, headaches, vision changes, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting.

treatment: Delivery of the baby and placenta is the only definitive treatment for pre-eclampsia. If the baby is not yet viable, medications may be used to control blood pressure and prolong the pregnancy.
description: An inflammation of the membranes that surround the brain and spinal cord, usually caused by a viral or bacterial infection.
prevalence: Approximately 1 in 10,000 people develop meningitis each year.

risk factors: Meningitis can occur at any age, but it is most common in young children and older adults. Certain medical conditions, such as sickle cell disease or HIV infection, can also increase the risk of meningitis.
symptoms: Fever, headache, stiff neck, rash, nausea, vomiting, light sensitivity, confusion.
treatment: Antibiotics (for bacterial meningitis) or antiviral medications (for viral meningitis).

prognosis: The prognosis for meningitis depends on the severity of the infection and the promptness of treatment. With early diagnosis and treatment, most people with meningitis make a full recovery. However, meningitis can be serious and even fatal if it is not treated.
